{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_jacobs_ver01/data/sn84020645/00513684265/1908042101/0279.xml":{"full_text":"CULLMAN CASE COMES\nFAMOUS PROHIBITION CASK IS DB\nCIDBD THURSDAY.\nFate of Two Haa*r\u00ab4 Doyoaao\nFrom Saprmo Coart\u2019o Dectoloa oa\nProhibition Cao\u00ab Coaa\nool la City.\nThe much-talked appeal of the case\nfrom' Cullman county which will set\ntle Anally the fate of more than two\nhundred men who are under Indict\nment for violation of the general pro\nhibition law of the State will be Aled\nThursday with the Alabama Supreme\nCourt. Thur^lay oral arguments will\nbe heard from both State and the ap\npellant.\nThis Information was brbught to\nMontgomery, yesterday by Colonel J.\nBascomb Brown, of Cullman, who spent\nthe day In the Supreme Court library\npreparing the brief of the State In the\ncase. Hon. Sidney J. Bowie, former\nCongressman, will appear for the ap\npellant.\nThe case to be decided Is that of Al.\nRichter v. State of Alahama In which\nRichter a saloon proprietor, of Cull\nman, was Indicted last February for\nan alleged violation of the prohibition\nlaw. He with several others kept open\ntheir saloons after January 1, 190S not\nwithstanding that before December 12,\n1907 the people of the county had voted\nliquor out by a good majority.\nCounsel for the State are contending\nthat prohibition went Into effect In\nCullman county by a provision of the\nprohibition statute which put prohibi\ntion into effect In all counties which\nhad voted \"dry\" prior to December 12.\n1907. It Is claimed that prohibition\nwent Into effect In Cullman on January\n1. 1901.\nThe main contention on which the\nappellant Is resting his case Is that the\nelection on December 9 last was In\nvalid in that It was held In less than\nthirty days after the same was ordered.\nThus a different brief will be Aled in\nthis case from that which entered into\nthe caee a few days ago decided by the\nSupreme Court, upholding the prohibi\ntion law.\nCounsel for the State in the Cullman\ncase, as Indicated by Colonel Brown\nyesterday, will answer the contention\nof the appellant's counsel by alluding\nto that part of Justice McClellan's\nopinion of a few days ago which left\nthe inference that whether the elec\ntions were Invalid or not. or whether\nthe law was unconstitutional or not,\nunder which dry elections were held,\nthe mere expression off the people's\nwill under color of the law sufficed to\nput prohibition Into effect in counties\nvo'lng dry prior to December 12 lost\nIf the Supreme Court affirms the\nJudgment of the Cullman Circuit Court,\nwhich was a conviction of the appel\nlant .the effect will be disastrous on\nthe more than two hundred other men\nwho are under indictment In Cullman\nCounty for similar violations. The sa\nloons are all open wide In Cullman to\nthis day. and If their test case falls\nbefore the Supreme Court they have\nrendered themselves liable for a sec\nond conviction. In the event of a sec\nond conviction, the law allows no dis\ncretion to the presiding Judge but he\nmust Impose the maximum penalty of\na 11.000 Ane and six months at hard\nlabor. The saloon men In Cullman are\noperating under llcer\u00abes which they\nobtained In regular manner from the\nProbate Judge of the county.\nColonel Brown said yesterday that\nthere will be an adjourned session of\nthe Cullman Circuit Court the Arst\nMonday In July. He predicts that the\nprohibition forces of the county will\nprosecute every alleged violator of the\nlaw if the case to be submitted to the\nSupreme Court Thursday falls.\nThe Supreme Court will be on the\nbench to hear the arguments of cases\nappealed from counties of the Sixth\nDivision. These are Blount, Cullman.\nFayette, Jefferson. Utnaf, Marion\nPickens. Tufealoosa. Walker god Wtus\nton.\nRailroad Makes Changes.\nNew Orleans. La.. April 2#.\u2014Effective\nMav 1 the Missouri PaclAc Railroad\nwill re-open Its freight office here,\nwhich recently wi closed on account\nof general flranclal condition*. W. H.\nReed will be tn charge a* general\nfreight agent. P. C. Patterson will\naucceed Hr. Reed as commercial agent\nof the Mobile and Ohio Railroad here.\nCHARITY OP MRS. BROWN.\nDiagktn of General Gordon a Settle\nment Worker.\nBerlin. N. H.. April M.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nMr*. O. B. Brown of thla town, daugh\nter of the famous Confederate General\nJohn B. Goordon and wife of Horton\nB. Brown the millionaire lumber op\nerator and wood pulp manufacturer. Is\nfast enshrining herself In the heart*\nof the working people In this place.\nShe ha* established settlement work\nin the \"Paper City,\u201d has started a\nclub for boy* and ha* organised a dis\ntrict nursing association by which\nmothers are taught to care for sick\nchildren.\nShe has established a reading room\nfor young men with a trained settle\nment worker In charge and herself at\ntimes gives them an entertainment In\nwhich her Imitations of Southern ne\ngroes are a factor.\nMR. CRAK\u2019S FUNERAL\nBODY LAID TO BEAT IB OAK\nWOOD CEMETERY.\nSbar Friend- Followed to Loot Rest\nIng Plan\u2014lenrleci Take Place\nFrom St. John's Eplseo\npal Ckarck.\nBy the deeth of Mr. G. W. Cralk On\nEaster Day, April 19. which waa alio\nhia birthday. Montgomery lost a citi\nzen whose conduct waa always baaed\nupon strong conviction and honest pur\npose. Those who had the pleasure of\nclose acquaintance with him apprecia\nted to the fullest degree his splendid\nmentality, his generous Judgment of\n.-non and measures and his kind, loving\nheart.\nHe filled many positions of honor and\ntrust and always to the complete satis\nfaction of those whose Interests were\ncommitted to his keeping. He was the\nvery embodiment of honor and his dally\nwa.k and life can well be taken as ex\namples of correct conduct by those who\nsurvive him.\nIdle large attendance at his funeral\nservices at St. John\u2019s Church yesterday\nafternoon, of friends from all denomi\nnations, attested the high esteem In\n\"which he was held. The profusion of\nflowers spoke eloquently the love of\nthose who affectionately regarded him\nwhile living and who will cherish his\nmemory now that he Is no more pres\n.ent among them.\nThe senvlces were conducted by Rev.\nE. E. Cobbs, rector of St. John's\nChurch and of which Mr. Cralk for\nmany years was a devoted and consis\ntent communicant\nA large number of sorrowing friends\nfollowed to the cemetery and at the\nclose of the services there, the benedic\ntion was pronounced by his brother.\nRev. Charles E. Cralk of Uoulsvllle,\nThe following gentlemen acted as\npallbearers: Judge J. B. Gaston, Dr.\nJ. L. Gaston and Messrs. A S. Wool\nfolk. W. A. Oayle. A. S Johnston.\nJ. Kirk Jackson. W. W. Screws and\nIgnatius Poliak.\nMrs. Blair Files Salt.\nBirmingham, April 20.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nBertha Blair, administratrix of the es\ntate of John Blair, has tiled suit In\nthe City Court here against the Re\npublic Iron and Steel Company for\n$25,000 damages for the death of the\nIntestate by being overcome with gas\nat the Thomas furnace near here a few\nmonths ago.\n\u201cNo Property, Not Even a anllt.\u201d\n\u25a0Birmingham, April 20.\u2014(Special.)\u2014\nEmma McFarlln today filed a petition\nin the United States Court asking to\nbe declared a bankrupt. The liabili\nties are placed at *2-50. \u201cNo real es\ntate.\u201d reads the petition, \u201cno personal\nproperty, not even a quilt.\u201d\nRATES RESTRAINED\nJVDGK JONES GRANTS THE FOR\nMAL ORDER.\nMerely ESMa Dplalaa ml Ceert Two\nWeeks Abo Denying Malian\nof State\u2019s Cosmsri Is Cel\nebrates Caase.\nJudge Thomas O. Jones of the Fed\neral Court of the Middle District of\nAlabama yesterday granted the formal\norder permanently restraining Jhe rate\nJaws of Alabama until their accuracy\nand matter could be Inquired Into. The\norder simply put Into effect the law as\ndeclared by Judge Jones In his opinion\nIssued two weeks ago. and denying In\ntoto the several motions of the State\u2019s\ncounsel.\nThe case at the conference held be\ntween the attorneys for the State and\nthe attorneys for the railroads yester\nday assumed no new Shape. The con\nference was held by agreement with\nJudge Jones on his notlflcatlon that he\nwould today dioplace the temporary or\nder by a permanent or\u00a3er\u201e one which\nwould remain In force until the rate\nacts had been Investigated.\nThe attorneys who attended the con\nference for the State were Attorney\nGeneral A. M. Garber. Judge 8. D.\nWeakley, Henry C. Selheimer and Hor\nace Strlngfellow.\nThe railroads were represented by\nGregory L. Smith of Mobile. George W.\nJones. J. Manley Foster and Congress\nman Sidney J. Bowie of Birmingham.\nSome little disagreement arose over the\nquestion of which side would pay the\ncourt coats. It was Anally determined\nthat they should be borne by the rail\nroads.\nThe law as held by Judge Jones, was\ncrystalUed into the formal order of\nyesterday. The order makes perma\nnent for investigation what has been\nonly temporary and was In fact only a\nroutine order of the court. Because of\nthe magnitude of the Issues\nhowever, all attorneys In the case were\nrequested to be present, for an arree\nment on minor matters to be contained\nIn the order. _\nBASEBALL MATINEE.\nBaseball matlaee today at _**\nCreaeeat, for ladles aad *ea\u00ableai\u00aba. Ad\nmlaaloa au!y M eeats.\nVaudeville at P\nHOMES FOR DELEGATES.\nBirmingham Plaualag for Suaday\nSchool Coaveatloa.\nBirmingham, April ^1*.\nThe committee on home. tor the Stata\nSunday School Convention, w*llchT'1'1\nbe held In Birmingham next week,\ntoday Issued a call onthepeopleto\nfurnish lists of rooms that ean be h\nand the accommodations.\nIt Is figured that between 1.500\u2022 and\n2.000 persons will be here, commencing\nAorll 27. For the first time In the his\ntoryof the State organisation, no ef\nfort will be made to furnish rooms and\naccommodations free of chars\u00ae to the\n4aiaMtM th\u00ab attendance having frown\nr.yo?dt?\u00abcthh,a possibility. Theprivate\n_ kAwAvor Arc to he thrown open\nto'The delegates \u201cat th. lowest possible\nC\u00b0T>siilv meetings are being held by\nr\u201c.yuKh\",\u2018\nworkers ever seen In the state.\nrailway men complain.\ncar Passeagers Violate Traasfer\n\u2022srsui\nKht and ^0*\u00aershCe\u00b0r?B,*HiygdonnM^n\nelr complaint to BherlRat,,*. of th.\niy morning about r> toW the\nr.H\u00ab tha\u2018t conductor, reported bun\nedi Of Violations Sunday and the\nlertff was arted to do somethin In\n.^thf. connection.\" said Sheriff\n\u201cOn the Square\u201d\nCopyright 1908 by Hart Schaffher Mar*\n\u00abTN the swim\u201d so far as clothes are concerned;\n1 that\u2019s the condition of every man who wears\nour fine clothes; weve got the stuff that gives distinction and\ncharacter to a man s looks; made for us by\nHart Schaffner Marx.\nYou\u2019ll find the most exclusive dressers\u2014clubmen, college men,\nbusiness men--all wearing these perfect clothes; and you 11 hnd\na lot of them ready for you in our store.\nCome on in; the clothes ire fine.\nR&nge in Price $18 to $37*5\u00ae\nCapitol Clothing Store\nS. Gfcssenheimer Co.\nHigdon. \"It la clearly a violation of\nthe law. though, for a person to give\na transfer to another, or to receive\na transfer, and If the company Insists\nI must make arrests. From what I\n'.earn some of the best people in town\nare violating the transfer laws adopt\ned by the last Legislature, and I re\ngret very much to have to proceed.\"\nIt seems from the complaints which\nreach the Sheriff\u2019s office that certain\npassengers have a systematic way of\nusing transfers. One man who lives In\nthe western part of the city and works\nin a remote part of town will get on a\ncar and ride to the center of the city\nwhere he will meet a man who lives\nIn the eastern part of the city, and\nworks In the western part. When\nthey meet they exchange transfers and\nsave 5 cents each. Then on Sundays\nwhole families are said to have ex\nchanged transfers.\nAPPARATUS COMES FOR\nTUBERCULOSIS EXHIBIT\nThe mother's Union of Montgomery\nhas planned to visit the Tuberculosis\nExhibition at 4 o'clock Thursday after*\nnoon, at which time It Is hoped that\nsome special attention will be given to\nthe toples In which the mothers are\nInterested. Mrs. Ray W. Rushton, Cor\nresponding Secretary, has reported to\nthe Exhibition management that Mrs.\nE A. Parker, with Mrs. William Led\nyard, has been appointed as a commit\ntee to co-operate with the Exhibition,\nand to make a study of the exhibits,\nwith a view to further aiding the lo\ncal campaign against this disease.\nEarly in the week arrangements will\nba made for the public schools and\nvarious other edflucatlonal Institutions\nof the city to visit the Exhibition at\nthe scheduled hours. After the opening\nWednesday, there will be hourly ses\nsions with the use of the stereoptlcon\nthroughout the day and evening. In ad\ndition to the special addresses by phy\nsicians and others.\nApparatus Is Received.\nNinety-two boxes, crates, trunks and\nbundles have been received at the old\nrirst Baptist Church. In preparation\nfbr the Installation of the American\nTuberculosis Exhibit next week. Ac\ncording to Dr. Glenn Andrews, Chair\nman of the Tuberculosis Exhibition\nCommittee, this car load of freight will\nenable the cltixens of Montgomery and\nInfluential representatlvesyof many Ala\nbama towns to get right In line with\nother enterprising communities through\nout the country In the battle against\nconsumption.\n\u201cThis exhibition will be open only\ntwo weeks,\" said Dr. Andrews, \u201cbut\nthere will be something doing all of\nthat time, and It Is expected that thous\nands will learn the real nature of tu\nberculosis and consumption and will so\n-live hereafter that they will have much\nless need for fearing the disease. At\nthree places In Kentucky. 50.000 people\nvisited this same exhibition. In Prov\nidence, R. I., there were 7,000 visitors\nin one day.\n\u201cThe purpose of the Exhibition Is\npurely educational. No cures will be\nsold, or remedies advertised\" said Dr.\nAndrews. \u201cThere will be no charge for\nadmission and no money wiU be made\nby any one from having the show here.\nBy means of models of buildings and\ntents, beautiful photographs and novel\ncharts the exhibit will demonstrate the\nrelation of occupation and living con\nditions to disease and death, and will\nemphasise the terrible ravages of con\nsumption among all classes. The re\nmovable causes of the high death\nrate among negroes and Indians and\nChinese will be made clear, and It will\nhe shown that the uninformed negro\nconsumptive may be a possible source\nof death to any member of the com\nmunity. even among those who may\nnot even have seen or known the orig\ninal source of Infection. Truly, every\nbody Is Interested In this exhibition.\"\nEASTER IN WBTUMPKA.\nIXMllnt Program of Exercises At the\nMehtodlet Charck.\nWetumpka, April 20\u2014 (Special.)\u2014\nJhhM'aV\"aMrV'.ee at the Methodl.t\nChurch Sunday night was beautifully\nexecuted by the Sunday School\nThe following elaborate program wae\nrendered to an Immense congregation.\nQuartette\u2014\u201cLo! In the Qrave He\nHoTmes\"erfd*8*t*\u201e. MCCUl\u2019e\"'\n\u00ab,R\u201cH^.r \"Ba,ter Wa,eam\u2014Ml\"\nSon*\u2014\u201cLife Evermore\u201d\u2014By the Chil\ndren\nClass Recitation\u2014\"He Is Risen\"_Bv\nnine girls.\nQuartette\u2014\"Seeking the Master\nMisses McCullers, Messrs. Holmes and\nReading\u2014\"Three Easter Mornings\"\u2014\nMiss Jettve Hornsby.\nSong\u2014\u201cLillie of. Easter\u201d\u2014By the\nChildren.\nClass Recitation\u2014\u201cLillies of Easter\"\n\u2014By the Children.\nReading\u2014\"When the Mists Have\nCleared Away\"\u2014Miss Mary Sue Till\nman.\nSong\u2014\u201cThe Beautiful I\u00abnd\"\u2014Misses\nBessie Lola Gamble and Ila Thorn\nhill\nAfter this program. W. L. Lancaster.\nSuperintendent of the Sunday School,\nawarded prises to Miss Genie Gamble.\nMaster John Gamble and Miss Lola\nMae Britt for raising the most money\nIn Sunday School for missionary work.\nThe Ladles' Auxiliary of the Baptist\nChurch will hold a strawberry festival\non the court house lawn tomorrow\nevening.\nE. J. Cain. C. G. MCMorrls and L. O.\nBedberry, spent yesterday In Tsllassee\nHenry Collins, of this city, and Miss\nBessie Harrington, of Eclectic, were\nmarried In Eclectic yesterday. Both of\nthe young people are popular In the\ncountv and their many friends are con\ngratulating them.\nPARAMOUNT ISSUES.\nSame of Them Ukrt) To Be Taaaed la to\nthe Aah Heap.\nWall Street Journal.\nSome eay there can he no return of\nprosperity until Roosevelt Is retired to\nprivate life. Others say that there\ncan be no return of prosperity until\nthe Standard Oil pays that f29,000,000\nfine and Harrlman and Ryan are de\nposed from financial power.\nSome say that there can be no revival\nof prosperity until Congress, with Its\n250 bills to regulate the railroads, ad\njourns. Others say that revival de\npends upon a physical valuation of the\nrailroads, made with a view to lower\nfreight rates.\nSome say that the future of the coun\ntry depends upon putting rich male\nfactors In Jail, while others declare\nthat It will go to ruin unless the an\narchists sre deported and the socialists\nsuppressed.\nSome say that the nation will be In\nvolved in moral wreck unless the stock\nexchange Is closed up. while others\nlust as insistently declare that there\nwill be industrial collapse unless the\ndoctrine of the closed shop Is over\nthrown\nSome sav that the most Important\nproblem before the people Is the revis\nion of the tarlfT. while others sav that\nall other problems fade into insignifi\ncance beside that of the prohibition of\nthe liquor traffic.\nSome declare that national safety de\npends on the maintenance of the right\nof private property and the inviola\nbility of contract, while others hold\nthat there can be no hope for the fu\nture until there Is a more equal dis\ntribution of wealth.\nA complete list of \u201cthe most Import\nant Issues before the country\" would\nfill an entire Issue of The Wall Street\nJournal, and It is constantly growing.\nIt Is barely possible that the time mav\nsoon arrive when the people will get\ntired of problems, and sweeping \"the\nmost important Issues\" into the dust\npan and thence Into the ash heap, will\nsimply go to work. Time and work are\ntha greatest solvers of problems In the\nworlds\nCRENSHAW PRIMARY\n4. F. WALKER EASY WINNER FOR\nTAX ASSESSOR.\nJ. M. Hors and CJ. \u00bbrk\u00ab Will Ran\nOff for Tax Collector\u2014Others\nIn Second Primary.\nLuvarna. April to.\u2014-(Special.!\u2014\u2014The\nflrat primary in Crenahaw County pass\ned off very quietly today.\nIn the race for Tax Collector, where\nthere were six contestants. J. M. Horn,\nthe present Incumbent, and G. B. Sykes\nwill have to run again for the nomina\ntion In the Anal primary on May IS.\nJames F. Walker had a landslide for\nTax Assessor, receiving about 1.000\nmore votea than his nearest opponent,\nA. H. Williamson.\nThe second race for County Treas\nurer will be between A. J. Soloman,\nthe present incumbent, and w\nBailey, while Professor C. K. Sharp,\nwho Is a candidate to succeed himself,\nand Professor Joseps E. Justice will go\nInto the second primary for Superin\ntendent of Education.\nO. O. Dickey was nominated for\nCountv Solicitor without opposition.\nC. C. Conney and J. O. 8trlnger, for\nCommissioners. First District.\nH. L. Hill and R. L. Richardson, Sec\nond District _\nA. S. Dlsmukes and C. F. K.rlcpat\nrick, Third District.\nJ. A. Hooks and J. C. Warrick In\nthe Fourth\nNAVAL BILL READY\nHOVSK COMMITTEE BENDS IT TO\nSENATE.\nCarrie* Kaomoui A**roprla\u00abloas, Bat\nBoth Legislative Braache* Oppose\nRoosevelt and Hobsoa aa\nEonr Battleships.\nWashington, April 20\u2014After con\nsideration of testimony for more than\ntwo hour*, tha House Committee on\nNaval Affairs reported the naval bill\nto the Senate. It carries *111,54*.549.\nan Increase of *7,579.021 over the\namount of the bill a* '.t waa prepared\nby the House.\nOn the battleship construction pro\ngram the Senate Committee adopted\nthe policy of the House, making no\nchange In the provision for two ves\nsels.\nThe President\u2019s message in regard to\nthe construction of four battleships\nwas not considered, as It was known\nthat the committee was not In favor\nof four vessels.\nAn appropriation of *1,800.000 was\nmade for the purchase of the colliers\nconstructed by the Fore River Ship\nbuilding Company. Other Important\namendments were made as follows:\nIncrease of 20 per cent In the pay\nof officers of the navy, and civilian\nprofessors and Instructors at the Naval\nAcademy, and of 10 per cent In the\npay of enlisted force. *8,553.969: an\nIncrease of the pay of president and\nofficers of mathematics, constructors,\nand civil engineer corps to equal that\nof officers of the same rank In the\nmedical and pay corps. *16,150.\nFor public works, additional appro\npriations were made as follows:\nPortsmouth. N. H.. *90.000; Norfolk.\nVa. $200,000; Puget Sound, $140,000.\nPearl Harbor. Hawaiian Islands, for\nnaval station and dry docks. *1,000 000;\nCharleston. *32.000; marine corps. *65,\n000.\nThe appropriation for the marine\ncorps, exclusive of public works, ag\ngregate $621,148.\nSeveral matters of general legislation\nwere recommended by the committee\nas follows:\nGiving the staff toe rank and title\nas now established for the staff corps\nof the army, but providing that In no\ncase shall this carry command.\nProviding for the establishment of a\nwomen's nurse corps In the navy.\nProviding that naval bands shall\nreceive remuneration for music fur\nnished in competition with clvlllar\nbands. _\nTha provision for tha Increase of the\nmarine corps is as follows:\nOne major-general commandant in\nplace of present brigadier-general\ncommandant; one lieutenant-colonel,\ntwo majors, eighteen captains, seven\nfirst lieutenants, and 